                                <p class="font-bold text-slate-900">PR Application</p>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600">With 1 year Canadian experience, apply through CEC. Alternatively, reach 2 years for BC PNP Skilled Worker eligibility.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 not-prose my-8">
                    <div class="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
                        <p class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Waiting for Graduate Streams</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-red-800">Don't assume suspended streams will reopen. Build your profile for existing pathways now.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
                        <p class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Ignoring Language Scores</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-red-800">CLB 8-9 dramatically improves your chances. Invest in test preparation early.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
                        <p class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Taking Any Job</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-red-800">TEER 4-5 jobs waste precious PGWP time. Hold out for skilled positions even if they pay less initially.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
                        <p class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Single Pathway Focus</p>
                        <p class="text-sm text-red-800">Apply to multiple programs simultaneously. BC PNP, Express Entry, and other PNPs can run in parallel.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <h3>Can I still get PR through BC PNP as a recent graduate?</h3>
                <p>
                    Yes, but not through graduate-specific streams. You'll need to qualify through the Skilled Worker stream (requiring 2 years experience), Tech stream (for eligible tech occupations), or Health Authority stream (for healthcare workers employed by BC health authorities).
                </p>

                <h3>Is it worth waiting for graduate streams to reopen?</h3>
                <p>
                    No. The province has stated there are "no concrete plans" for new graduate streams in 2026. Build your profile for existing pathways instead of waiting for uncertain future options.
                </p>

                <h3>What if my PGWP expires before I get PR?</h3>
                <p>
                    If you've submitted a valid PR application, you can apply for a Bridging Open Work Permit (BOWP) to maintain work authorization while waiting for PR processing. However, you must apply before your PGWP expires.
                </p>

                <h3>Should I consider studying a second credential?</h3>
                <p>
                    Possibly. A shorter credential in healthcare (HCA) or early childhood education (ECE) could qualify you for priority sector targeted draws, potentially faster than general skilled worker pathways.
                </p>

                <h3>Is Express Entry or BC PNP better for graduates?</h3>
                <p>
                    It depends on your profile. Express Entry (CEC) requires only 1 year of Canadian experience but has competitive CRS cutoffs. BC PNP requires 2 years of experience but adds 600 CRS points if you also have an Express Entry profile, virtually guaranteeing an invitation.
                </p>

                <hr class="my-10 border-slate-200" />

                <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

                <p>
                    The suspension of BC PNP graduate streams is disappointing but not insurmountable. Thousands of international students successfully transition to permanent residency each year through alternative pathways. The key is starting early, building a strong profile, and pursuing multiple options simultaneously.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Focus on what you can control: language scores, work experience accumulation, and strategic career choices. The students who succeed in 2026 will be those who adapt their strategies to the current reality rather than hoping for policy changes that may never come.
                </p>

